    <div class="attribute-header">
        <h1><a href="/Mirror/eZ-Systems-Blog">eZ Systems Blog</a></h1>
     </div>
    <div class="attribute-header">
        <h2>> <a href="http://ez.no/About-eZ/Blog/High-performance-one-of-the-many-very-good-reason-s-to-move-to-eZ-Publish-5.x" title="High performance, one (of the many) very good reason(s) to move to eZ Publish 5.x ">High performance, one (of the many) very good reason(s) to move to ...</a></h2>
     </div>

    <div class="attribute-byline">
	    </div>

    

    <div class="attribute-body float-break">
      <p>So there is one thing that is sure about eZ Publish 5, and certainly understated: <b>eZ Publish 5 is the way to go for top-notch performance!</b></p><p>It has always been clear, speaking about traditional Content Management Systems (CMS), including eZ Publish 3 &amp; 4: making these systems run fast under heavy load was a true challenge. This was sometime a very critical topic for anyone running high-traffic apps. Well, we should may be say it more clearly and loudly: eZ Publish Platform 5 and further solve this issue, thanks to its architecture and the way it integrates the Symfony2 framework. Release after release, this will keep improving. If you have a high-traffic site to build and think using a CMS will not make it for the sake of performance, you should probably reconsider your position before reinventing the wheel.</p><p>Hereafter are a few facts that our benchmark are showing to better understand how eZ Publish evolve in that respect.</p><p>(to better understand the last part of it, you might want to make sure you understand the dual-kernel architecture of eZ Publish 5 which is for instance <a href="https://confluence.ez.no/x/kgGu" title="Confluence - eZ Architecture" target="_blank">introduced here</a>.</p><a name="eztoc390149_1" id="eztoc390149_1"></a><h2>Sites based on the &quot;New Stack&quot;are breaking the barrier</h2><p>By “New Stack”, we mean sites using eZ Publish 5.x with a front end done with the new Web stack, Twig and Symfony based (and not the legacy system).</p><p>The graph below is taken from our bench, on the standard eZ Demo site. It shows the number of pages delivered by a simple small box running standard eZ Publish installations. With 5.2, we have roughly been multiplied by 4 since eZ Publish 4.7 - it speaks by itself.</p><p>You could see this as a way to divide by 4 your hardware infrastructure cost. More importantly, it says high-performance are getting more and more delivered out-of-the-box, without the need for extra layers and sophisticated tunings. This also saves costs.</p><p>This is something people should have in mind when evaluating whether to use Symfony “New Stack” or the legacy stack on new projects.</p>
<div class="object-center"><div class="content-view-embed">
	<div class="class-image">
		<div class="attribute-image">

	
															
		
		
														
										
													
													
						
			<a href="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/graphic2/390163-1-eng-GB/graphic_fancybox.png" rel="fancybox" class="fancybox"><img src="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/graphic2/390163-1-eng-GB/graphic_medium.png" width="462" height="235" style="border: 0px solid ;" alt="" title="" /><span title="Enlarge this image"></span></a>		
		
		
	</div>
			</div>
</div>
</div><p>To add to this graph, while 450 pages per second on such a configuration is really not bad, it must be highlighted that it is only a benchmark on a standard out-of-the-box server. No clustering, no optimized configuration, no big muscle.</p><p>For more performance and clustering setups, Varnish Cache is the plugin replacement to go for. With the same unique tight integration between eZ Publish and the Varnish Cache as the default cache benchmarked above, you can get many thousand requests per second and beyond without sacrificing anything in terms of making sure your content is up to date online. In addition such a setup removes most of the load on your web servers, making it handle peaks in a much better way. We will try to share more on what can be expected when optimizing the stack in future blog posts to give a real idea of what can be achieved.</p><a name="eztoc390149_2" id="eztoc390149_2"></a><h2>Pure legacy stacks remains what it was, combining legacy and the new stack has some clear limitations that shall be known</h2><p>As I mentioned before, eZ Publish 5 is complex to understand, as it has a complex dual-kernel architecture. One should not necessarily read too quickly and make sure he understands in which configuration he is.</p><p>I will try to summarize simply, we can basically see 3 main ways to use eZ Publish 5:</p>
<ul>

<li>New Stack: using the new Symfony based architecture and Twig based templates.</li>

<li>Hybrid: using the legacy within the new stack, authorizing everything that was done in legacy, but going through the new kernel and the Symfony stack.</li>

<li>Pure legacy: using only the legacy part, as you would use eZ Publish 4.7.</li>

</ul>
<p>(note: there is also a “legacy mode” in the Hybrid approach that is <a href="http://share.ez.no/blogs/jerome-vieilledent/legacy_mode-clarified" title="legacy mode clarified blog" target="_blank">discussed here</a>&nbsp;and should not be confused with this “pure legacy” &nbsp;approach)</p><p>This other figure below shows the numbers we got for an eZ Flow page using both the hybrid approach combining Legacy &amp; New stack and the Pure legacy approach.</p>
<div class="object-center"><div class="content-view-embed">
	<div class="class-image">
		<div class="attribute-image">

	
															
		
		
														
										
													
													
						
			<a href="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/hybrid_model-graphic/390167-1-eng-GB/hybrid_model-graphic_fancybox.png" rel="fancybox" class="fancybox"><img src="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/hybrid_model-graphic/390167-1-eng-GB/hybrid_model-graphic_medium.png" width="462" height="207" style="border: 0px solid ;" alt="" title="" /><span title="Enlarge this image"></span></a>		
		
		
	</div>
			</div>
</div>
</div><p>And if we focus on the Pure Legacy approach, the graphs above and below gives a good overview: using pure legacy is really in the continuity and if you would make the choice to go “Pure legacy”, you can really expect the eZ Publish 4.x standard behaviors - and we surely will support this a long time for people who still love the legacy stack.</p><div class="separator"><span></span></div>
<div class="object-center"><div class="content-view-embed">
	<div class="class-image">
		<div class="attribute-image">

	
															
		
		
														
										
													
													
						
			<a href="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/aver-nr-pages_graphic/390171-1-eng-GB/aver-nr-pages_graphic_fancybox.png" rel="fancybox" class="fancybox"><img src="http://ez.no/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/media/images/aver-nr-pages_graphic/390171-1-eng-GB/aver-nr-pages_graphic_medium.png" width="462" height="297" style="border: 0px solid ;" alt="" title="" /><span title="Enlarge this image"></span></a>		
		
		
	</div>
			</div>
</div>
</div><a name="eztoc390149_3" id="eztoc390149_3"></a><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>
Sharing some information, (honestly and not tweaked by marketeers) on these benchmarks is important to us and I hope it is useful to the people planning new projects. Our engineering team will surely provide much more detailed information on the topic, including the detail of the test protocols and other things. Feel free to anticipate and discuss it on the <a href="http://share.ez.no/forums" title="Share forums" target="_blank">share.ez.no </a><a href="http://share.ez.no/forums" id="__mce_tmp" title="Share forums" target="_blank">forums</a>.<br />What can be said for now is:</p>
<ul>

<li>You want your eZ Publish to fly? The new architecture will make this happen, and we can thank the cache approach provided by Symfony2 framework for this, further extended in eZ Publish to integrate it tightly into the eZ Publish 5 Content repository and it's advance capabilities. <b>If you want to build for High Performance, think New Stack &amp; Symfony!</b></li>

<li>If you are conservative, or a fan of our old templating engine, may be you should consider the “pure legacy” approach, you will not be surprised at all in regards to performances.</li>

<li>If you fall in between the two approach (may be because you have existing code to keep with you), you need to be careful, high-performance can be reached but they need extra tuning, potentially additional caching components and a smart design and code of your site.</li>

</ul>
<p>If you want to know more about other good things that are in the 5.2 release, there will be more details very soon about the 5.2 Release Webinar. Stay tuned!</p>
    </div>

